The drug for 2 pounds per day can reduce the risk of heart attack.
Thousands of patients who have had a heart attack could be treated with 2 pounds per day, as official representatives recommend more and more people.
The anti-cloking drug Ticagrelor reduces the risk of repeated heart attacks in people with heart disease.
This medicine is already prescribed for use for 12 months after the heart attack, reducing the risk of repeated cardiac arrest.
NHS-represented NICE recommends the use of this preparation for 4 years after heart attack to further reduce the risk of heart attack in people with cardiovascular problems.
However, NICE currently under the control of the NHS recommends the use of this preparation for 4 years after the heart attack to further reduce the risk of the heart and blood vessels.
Approximately 140 000 people in England experience a heart attack each year, and a quarter of whom experience a repeated heart attack or stroke.
Heart attack and stroke are caused by the accumulation of fatty substances in the walls of the heart, forming blockages.
If the blockage ruptures, it can cause a clot, blocking the blood flow to the heart and causing a heart attack.
In turn, if the clot separates from the vascular wall, it can get further into the bloodstream and block blood access to the brain, causing a heart attack.
People who have had a heart attack are at greater risk of repeated heart attack.
Ticagrelor, produced by British firm AstraZeneca and traded under the name Brilique, reduces the risk of blood clots.
The new NICE guidelines, which was published today, are recommended for humans for 90 mg for 12 months and for another 3 years of 60 mg twice daily with aspirin.
Professor Carol Longson, director of NICE health technology, explains: "Despite the availability of medications to prevent repeated heart attack, more than a quarter of people who have had a heart attack experience another heart attack or stroke, which often has severe consequences."
Fear of repeated heart attacks can have a negative impact on the quality of human life.
Evidence suggests that Ticaglor, combined with aspirin, is effective at reducing the risk of repeated heart attack and heart attack in people who have already experienced it.
Preliminary recommending treatment with Ticagrelor, we are pleased that we can expand the treatment options for thousands of people who are thus benefiting.
In view of the limited information on the efficacy and safety of Ticagror, particularly the risk of bleeding with this medicinal product for more than three years, the draft guidelines do not recommend its use longer than this period.
