According to a new study, the number of fatalities at the communist yoke of the former East German border could be much higher than previously thought, but doubts about the true number of victims are still not allayed.
According to data released on Wednesday by the Berlin Wall Museum Checkpoint Charlie, between 1945 and 1989, 1841 people who have tried to get out of their territory were murdered by the communist authorities of Western Germany, from 1945 to 1989.
The museum has been studying border-related deaths for years and occasionally corrects the number of victims.
This year, another 11 deaths have been added to the list, including a six-year-old boy who drowned a family trying to get to West Germany through the then Czechoslovakia and Hungary.
Among the new victims of the Berlin Wall are also defectors of the Soviet army.
"The final extent of the damage caused by the dual evil of communism and socialism has not yet been fully documented," admits the museum's director, Alexander Hildebrante.
"Our task is to ensure that the graves of those who died in an effort to escape from a communist-controlled country are being groomed and not disappeared," Hildebrandt's statement said in a statement released by Hildebran.
But other researchers have already questioned the new figures.
"The number 1841 is inconclusive," Johens Statt, an expert in the history of the Free University of Berlin, said in an interview with the newspaper Süddeutsche Zeitung.
Together with other researchers from the Free University of Berlin, he is currently reviewing the alleged suspicious deaths at the border, and so far they have managed to confirm only 260 cases.
Previously, researchers estimated that only on the Berlin Wall, communists murdered 138 people.
In view of those people who died trying to escape the Baltic Sea or get to the West through the territory of neighboring countries, the number of victims could reach about a thousand.
However, this is still significantly less than 1841.
One of the reasons for the number of different victims could be different methodologies.
Checkpoint Charlie Museum also lists all cases of suicide by East German border guards, regardless of whether they were directly related to their service.
The museum also lists deaths that are not related to direct violence.
"If seniors aged 70 to 80 years after shrinking with border controls died of heart attack, it should have consequences for this "lander border," Hildebrante believes.
But the State is convinced that a distinction must be made between the old people who may have died as a result of their treatment and those whose death is caused by a prolonged wait in hot weather on the bus at the border.
Regardless of its, the records of the victims are not easy, as the Communist East German authorities did not collect such statistics, and researchers should examine the documents in various scattered archives, says Stat.
However, the State Group has recently found new documents and could therefore come up with a new estimate of the number of victims in the near future.
