A French court dismissed Calais' authorities' request to demolish dozens of self-created shops and restaurants in the Jungle camp, where several thousand refugees live.
At a hearing this week in Calais, the authorities indicated that the state should quench 72 self-made shops, where people sell various goods in the camp area, such as cigarettes and energy drinks, offer hairdressing services, tea for 50 cents (40p) and simple meals for a few euros in self-created restaurants.
The Prefect Office of Kale pointed out that these self-made companies must be demolished because they form the shadow economy and do not pay taxes, as well as create fire and sanitary risks.
Representatives of the humanitarian group explained to the court that these small businesses are essential, as food provided by the government and the support groups does not meet the needs of the camp, in which the number of occupants continues to grow.
They also pointed out that self-made boutiques and restaurants often offer free shelter and food for those who need it most.
The Lille court ruled that there was no legal basis for expulsions of people who have created 72 self-made stores, but it understands the concerns of the Prefect of Calais.
Judge Jean-France Molla said food, coffee and restaurants play a bigger role than simply providing food to people who live in "extremely humble conditions."
He pointed out that these places are peaceful meeting places for refugees and volunteers.
One of the places at risk of demolition is the Jungle Book Kids Café, which provides more than 200 free meals a day, English and French language classes and advises on asylum issues hundreds of vulnerable minors without adult companions.
More than 170 000 people have signed a petition on the protection of a children's cafe.
A letter addressed to the Guardian stated that the liquidation of the cafe "should be a disaster for these children, some of whom are only 8 years old."
On Friday, two charities "Help for Refugees" and "L'Auberge des Migrants" reported that the number of residents of the "Jungle" camp has increased to 9000 people, the highest figure since the rapid influx of migrants in the summer.
