In Spain, the possibility of reducing the budget deficit is threatened by the inability to form a government.
A month ago, on 12 July, the European Commission (EC) issued an opinion that Spain and Portugal had not taken sufficient measures to reduce the deficit level to the 3% of gross domestic product (GDP) requested by the euro area.
Estimates that despite the austerity measures implemented, Portugal's deficit was 4.4% of GDP at the end of last year and 5.1% in Spain.
However, the European Commission decided not to impose economic sanctions on both countries, while at the same time setting fiscal targets for the near term.
One of the reasons why the EC, however, did not introduce sanctions against the two countries mentioned is the growing Euroscepticism in many countries of the European Union.
Additional sanctions would only increase such negative sentiment.
Critics, however, point out that the EC is not consistent in its decisions, from the beginning agreeing on uniform rules and then unable to apply them in life.
Thus, for example, the President of the German Bundesbank Jens Weidmann has pointed out that Europe loses its credibility in this way, creating the perception that the European Union's rules are recommendative, not binding.
The EC has now proposed and all Member States have approved an extension of the deadline for the adoption of the deficit until the end of this year for Portugal and for Spain until 2018.
The European Commission promises to examine the progress made by both countries in the coming months, at the same time pointing out that both Spain and Portugal should be prepared to introduce additional austerity measures if circumstances so require.
The initial forecasts suggest that Portugal's target could be achieved in due time and already this year the budget deficit could fall to 2.5% of gross domestic product.
This means that, as part of the Stability Programme, the government of this country must implement austerity measures of 0.25% of GDP this year.
These measures should be included in this year's budget, with an additional focus on controlling the purchase costs of goods and services.
In the case of Spain, the situation is much more complicated.
This year, the budget deficit should be reduced to 4.6%, next year - to 3.1% and in 2018 - to 2.2% of GDP.
In addition, consolidation measures in the next two years should be 0.5% of GDP per year.
