"The main source is the visitors of the beach themselves, because more than half of the total number of waste is plastic, various waste, starting with bags, plastic pieces that are already in the degradation stage, they are no longer possible to identify them, and for butts, bottles, corks," says Ulme.
Among the dirtiest beaches are also bathing places in Riga.
For example, in Daugavgriva, on average, almost 800 waste units have been collected every hundred meters, which is a critically a lot.
The organizers of the campaign also explain that almost every step of the way also tossing the signs of warning or prohibition are placed everywhere.
"The average figures for all three Riga bathing sites together - Daugavgriva, Evening Bulls and Vecāķi - unfortunately come together large and far beyond the desired or the goal to which Latvia is supposedly moving, to reduce the number of waste units to 135 units by 2020," concludes the environmental defender.
The cleaning of bathing places in Riga takes place every day, on the hottest days of summer even twice, explains the representative of the Council Uģis Vidauskis.
However, the fight with the dirty visitors is quite difficult.
We are returning to the cultural issue of these people.
"Those who litter, drink alcohol, smoke and do all those things that can not, even special signs do not work," Vidauskis points out.
Therefore, Vidauskis is asking visitors to report polluted pollutants to the police as well.
Can be called the police, boldly point out these violations and in this way everyone fight.
Perhaps some new warnings can be put on, but as I said, it will hardly change the situation as radically.
"Since everyone must simply turn together and be intolerant of such transgressors," he stresses.
Meanwhile, water quality measurements have been carried out for the fourth time this summer by the Health Inspectorate, which can impose a ban on official bathing sites.
This year, like other years, the quality of water is good and satisfactory everywhere.
At the moment, the situation is that in all 56 bathing areas the water quality has been good all the time and there are no bathing restrictions.
"For the last time we will take the analysis at the end of August", says Normunds Kadiķis, Senior Environmental Health Specialist of the Inspectorate.
During heavy rainfall, the land-based waste can be washed into the water.
