Before the 40th anniversary of "Līvu" the legendary rock band can be introduced to the exhibition in Liepaja.
The exhibition will feature various objects characterizing "Līvus" - photographs arranged in the timeline to reflect the group's activities from the beginning to 2010 when the end of the group's activities are announced.
Participants’ stage costumes, musical instruments, awards and concert recordings will also be shown, as well as other things that have not yet been seen by the general public that reflected the creative work of the band "Līvi".
The exhibition will be supplemented with objects of the collection of the Liepāja Museum.
The visual design of the exhibition was created in collaboration with fashion artist and painter Elita Patmalniece.
The musicians who have been associated with the band "Līvi" and their relatives also responded to the call and shared both objects and memories.
The origins of "Līvu" can be traced back to 1972, when a vocal instrumental ensemble was created in the Liepāja Culture House, which was led by Juris Pavitols.
The ensemble participated in its original composition at the festival "Liepājas dzintars" in 1972 and 1974, as well as in the city and republican shows.
In 1976, a fateful meeting took place, when Juris Pavitols met Ēriks Ķiģelis and the Metalurgs Culture Palace founded a group inviting Ingrīda Gūtmanis, Andris Krūziņš and Jānis Grodums to join.
Over the years, the composition of the group has changed more than once.
Participants have joined, others have gone their own way, some have returned.
However, the most important thing - the desire to confirm that Latvian rock music is able to live and exist - has remained unchanged.
"What to see was not lacking - jeans, hairy and bearded, these boys were noticeably different from the generally accepted stereotype of the stage singer," says music reviewer Klass Vāvere about the band.
The band has such outstanding musicians as Igo, Vilnis Krieviņš, Modris Šterns, Valdis Štarks, Laimis Rācenājs, Tālis Pusbarnieks, Ainars Virga, Aivars Brize, Guntars Mucenieks, Dainis Virga, Tomass Kleins and many others.
Entrance to the exhibition is free of charge.
The exhibition is open from August 19 to October 30.
