Based on NASA's latest climate models, Venus has once been a habitable planet.
Scientists at the NASA Godard Space Research Institute have developed a model to explore the history of Venus using tools and algorithms that are also used by climate scientists.
The model was designed to determine whether on Venus, the surface of which is hot, where there is no water and whose atmosphere consists almost exclusively of carbon, have once been Earth-like conditions.
Scientists have previously made it guess that Venus' slow speed of rotation is explained by the dense atmosphere.
But the latest simulations show that Venus once had a thin, Earth-like atmosphere and it turned slowly.
The model also looks at Venus's earlier topography.
There have been more dry areas on the planet than on Earth, but there was enough water and geographical diversity on it, so that life can be formed and prevented from evaporating water.
In the early years of Venus, the Sun was 30 percent brighter.
In the simulation of the GISS model, the spin pattern of Venus reveals that the bright part of the day on it lasts 2 months, explained GIS scientist Antonija Del Genio in a press release.
This process heats the surface of the planet and causes rain, which in turn forms thick layers of clouds, acting as an umbrella, protecting the planet from the heat of the Sun.
As a result, a moderate climate temperature is formed, which is actually a few degrees lower than the temperature on Earth today.
The model depicts the history of Venus, similar to the theory of evolution developed by scientists in its hypotheses.
Although it was once habitable, over the course of billions of years Venus has been exposed to too much heat and ultraviolet rays.
They effervesered by the oceans, and the spirits were burned out by ultraviolet rays.
When the water was completely evaporated, only a thin atmosphere of carbon dioxide with a deadly greenhouse gas remained - Venus as we know it today.
Scientists published the results of the new Venus climate model in the journal Geophysical Research Letters.
Patrick Roy resigns as Avalanche coach
On Thursday, the Colorado Avalanche coach and vice-president of hockey operations Patrick Roy filed a resignation, citing the lack of influence in the team's decision-making process.
The vice president and general manager of the Colorado, Joe Sakik, confirmed the news and informed that the club will immediately begin to look for a new coach.
"For the last three years, I have been vigorously, enthusiastic and purposefully performing my duties as head coach and vice president of the Colorado club's hockey operations," 50-year-old Roy said in a statement.
During this summer, I've been thinking a lot about how I could improve the performance of the team to give it the perfection and achieve higher-level results.
To achieve this, the visions of the head coach and vice president of hockey operations must fully coincide with the visions of the organization.
He must also be able to influence decisions relating to the performance of the team.
These conditions are not met at the moment.
Sakis, who hired Roy on May 23, 2013, thanked Roy for his contribution to the team.
Sakik said Patrick informed him today about his decision.
We appreciate everything he has done for the organization and wish him all the best in the future.
In his first season with the Avalanche team in 2013-2014, Roy was named the league's best coach and received the Jack Adams Award.
He helped the club reach 112 points and first place in the Central Division, but in the first round of the playoffs, the Colorado team was beaten by the Minnesota hockey players. Since then, the club hasn't entered the playoffs for two years.
Avalanche finished the 2015-2016 season with a score of 39-39-4 and remained five points behind the Wild team, without getting the second special invitation of the Western Conference organizers.
The Hall of Fame goaltender Roy won four Stanley Cups in his career - two with the Montreal Canadiens and two with Avalanche.
North Sea oil rig workers resume talks and postpone strike
Staff strikes on the remuneration of North Sea oil platform workers have been postponed as both parties to the dispute resumed talks, talks said.
Periodically, the oil processing company "Wood Group" is holding strikes on the North Sea oil equities operating the Royal Dutch Shell.
The joint statement said that the Wood Group and Unite and the MRM unions have agreed to resume negotiations on resolving the dispute.
Several full-day meetings are scheduled to start early next week with the aim of re-examining issues.
The unions said their recent events, organised after a break of more than 25 years, are against the planned wage cut of 30 per cent.
Due to negative market pressures, the Wood Group cut salaries for workers in the North Sea this year by 9 percent.
Already in 2014, the company cut the wages of land workers by 10 percent.
The company explains that additional wage cuts would allow the company to survive the market downturn.
In turn, Shell already cut wages of several thousand people and announced plans to stop oil and natural gas in 10 countries to optimize its work in preparing for a large-scale merger deal with the British energy company BG Group.
Energy companies are feeling pressure due to falling oil prices, and the situation is further complicated by Britain's decision to leave the European Union.
Earlier in the week, Scottish MP Dave Anderson met with workers' representatives to discuss one of the most important issues - the North Sea strike plans.
He said the North Sea is vital for the economy of the region.
In his report, he explains that the North Sea and the country as a whole need an economy that benefits all, not individual individuals.
In 2016, new North Sea projects are expected to invest nearly $1.4 billion, compared with $7 billion invested over the past five years.
Keplers size star spin speed in the constellation of Pleiades.
The mission of the latest Kepler telescope has helped astronomers gather the most complete catalog of star rotation speed in the constellation of Plyad.
The new data helps astronomers understand why stars in this constellation are spinning at different speeds, as well as how the rotational speed of stars refers to planetary formation.
"We hope that comparing our results with other constellations, we will get more information about the connection between the star mass, age and even the history of its solar system," the Pasadena Caltech Infrared Process and Analytical Center scientist Luisa Rebula told reporters in a news release.
The constellation of Plyad is located 445 light-years away from Earth.
Many stars in this constellation are only beginning to rise, reaching the age of about 125 million.
They shall rotate at the maximum speed.
Turning at the maximum speed, these growing stars give off a large amount of star wind.
When the winds enter the magnetic field of the stars, they brake the stars.
As the stars age, their spin speed decreases.
Kepler measures the speed of rotation of each star, determining the time between the appearance of a recognizable star area, such as solar spots.
The latest star spin speed directory suggests that larger stars spin slower than smaller stars.
Rebull compares stars with dancers, larger dancers make pirouettes more slowly than small dancers.
Rebuls tells that the "ballet" of Pleiades shows that the slow rotating objects are larger and more massive, while the faster rotating objects are very small stars.
Thanks to the fact that the constellation of Pleiades is so close, it serves as an excellent space laboratory, where you can compare the characteristics of the stars with the speeds of rotation.
Rebuls tells that the constellation of Pleiades helps to create theoretical models of star rotation in both directions for both older and younger stars.
We still have a lot to learn how, when and why the speed of star rotation slows down and the process of stopping for it.
Rebull and his colleagues presented in detail the analysis of the speed of the stars of Pleiades in three new publications, which will soon be published in the Astronomical Journal.
